  "notes": "Kabiye (Kabɩyɛ) of Togo, written in a Latin orthography based on the African reference alphabet, in which most letters are the IPA symbol of the phoneme they write (ɖ, ɩ, ʊ, ɛ, ɔ, ŋ). ⟨c⟩=/tʃ/, ⟨j⟩=/dʒ/, ⟨ñ⟩=/ɲ/, ⟨y⟩=/j/; ⟨kp⟩ and ⟨gb⟩ are labial-velar stops. Long vowels are written doubled, which the map handles as a sequence of two identical vowels. Kabiye has two tones (H, L) with automatic downstep; tone is not marked in the standard orthography, so no tone marks are emitted. ATR vowel harmony pairs ɩ/i, ʊ/u, ɛ/e, ɔ/o.",
